.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical time between consuming contaminated food and onset of symptoms in Staphylococcus aureus food poisoning?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1-6 hours","8-16 hours","12-24 hours","24-48 hours","48-72 hours"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E food poisoning, symptoms typically appear within \u003Cstrong\u003E1-6 hours\u003C/strong\u003E after ingestion of contaminated food. This rapid onset occurs because the bacteria produce preformed heat-stable enterotoxins in the food before consumption. The toxins cause acute nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other time periods represent different food-borne illnesses:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E8-16 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of \u003Cem\u003EBacillus cereus\u003C/em\u003E diarrhoeal syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E12-24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of \u003Cem\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/em\u003E food poisoning\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is more consistent with \u003Cem\u003ESalmonella\u003C/em\u003E species infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E48-72 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is similar to the incubation period for viral gastroenteritis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe short incubation period of \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E food poisoning is due to direct action of preformed toxins, rather than requiring bacterial growth or invasion in the host.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Food poisoning caused by Staphylococcus aureus results from preformed heat-stable enterotoxins that cause symptoms within 1-6 hours.","Bacillus cereus can cause two distinct food poisoning syndromes: an emetic syndrome from cereulide toxin and a diarrhoeal syndrome from enterotoxins.","Clostridium perfringens food poisoning occurs when heat-resistant spores germinate in cooling food and produce enterotoxins."],"references":["Switaj TL, Winter KJ, Christensen SR. Diagnosis and Management of Foodborne Illness. Am Fam Physician. 2015;92(5):358-365."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51737"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16678"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51737"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T18:29:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:33:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9369"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66288"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations